He also describes ordinary or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood" together, there are "gray cars" and "gray land" in the valley of ashes, the "Italian child" on the railroad is "gray," and the dog-seller is "a gray old man."

Once Fitzgerald imbues enough meaning into white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or uniformity in certain subjects. This use of colors to show readers something starts with Daisy. After a long time without significant use of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster"; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a distinct character and more of a uniform addition, something that Gatsby desires and longs for. Fitzgerald uses more of this technique around Daisy to reinforce this impression of her as a more uniform addition, for example, there is a "gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar," and she is again in a "white" dress before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is highly productive in agriculture due to its mild and sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits such as peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a notable market for organic community-supported agriculture in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also very popular. Many organic farms offer tours of their agricultural operations and provide opportunities for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This type of operation allows landowners to benefit from government programs while improving habitats, thus permitting recreational use and creating opportunities for farm tours and other programs for profit or educational purposes.

In addition to fulfilling a potentially lucrative niche market, organic farming often benefits from greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife due to the absence of chemicals in soil and water. However, organic farming can be more costly than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more labor and management to remove pests and weeds and to fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater compared to conventional methods. Small organic farms also lack the scale efficiency of large operations. Practices unrelated to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur higher labor costs, such as planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and actively managing plant growth to provide specific conditions like edge habitats or open patches of ground. Therefore, in this example, the landowner might seek financial assistance or expertise to maximize both profit and habitat quality.

The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It comprises 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still under review, but it currently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals, many of which are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher; others, like burrowing owls, are declining and may soon be listed.

This area was inhabited by Native Americans for countless centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and was likely used for grazing and/or wood production for many intervening decades.

A piece of property was chosen from a real estate website, and available government programs were researched to determine what options a small farmer might realistically have to mitigate costs and maintain wildlife-friendly operations. As a model for what someone farming this land might try to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers that is unbreakable and irrevocable. Within this bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, to name a few. Brothers understand each other more than anyone else with such a bond, and they see themselves when looking at their brother. It is in the most dire situations that the true nature of this bond is revealed, whether for good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry a great cost. Part of understanding the emotions born from this fraternal link is addressing the consequences they bring. When one looks into a brother's eyes and sees their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. Their true character is revealed in their actions and the consequences of those actions. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this theme and the turbulent emotions that accompany it. Through a lush and vividly described landscape, these two boys embark on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother survives. The theme is expressed through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which conveys the protagonist's complex emotions and his view of the world, greatly influencing his actions.

The protagonist's actions can be summarized by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels a sense of resentment towards Doodle. He wanted a brother to whom he could teach all his worldly skills, like "holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp..." He desired a brother who could "race to Horsehead Landing with him...and perch with him in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn..." Obviously, these things are impossible given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making his survival unlikely. Even then, it was nearly impossible for him to engage in vigorous physical activity. To the young protagonist, whose mind was filled with wild fantasies, having all those dreams crushed was a significant blow. In fact, he even harbors some anger towards the small child, as he recalls contemplating killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would consider such an act of infanticide? However, his heart softens when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist hope! This indicates that his conviction was probably not very strong. Deep down, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complex and creative information-processing system. As technology has evolved from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain have also evolved. Initially, it was likened to a wax tablet, then papyrus, then a book, and more recently, a computer. When learning about the brain, remember that these metaphors have limited utility and can lead to incorrect conclusions.

Information processing begins with input from sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. Sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the brain's algorithms through bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when viewing an image of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing integrates simple information such as color, orientation, and where the object's edges are, where color changes significantly over a short distance, to determine that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses decisions made at certain steps of the bottom-up process to speed up recognition of the box. In this case, top-down processing might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.

Once information is processed to a certain extent, an attention filter determines the importance of the signal and which cognitive processes it should be directed to. For example, while your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from focusing on them individually. Conversely, you might notice your name even in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and attention repeatedly modulates the results.

For the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are several types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term memory. First, information is encoded, with each type of sensory stimulus having specific encoding methods. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to the appearance of printed words, phonemically, referring to the sound of the words, or semantically, referring to the meaning of the words. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for about 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short time. Long-term memory information is believed to be maintained by the structure of certain types of proteins.

There are numerous models of how knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on how humans retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others on neurophysiology. The semantic network model suggests there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, "chair" might be linked to "table," which in turn can be linked to "wooden," and so on.

In 2007, the United States was hit by a severe financial crisis. Unemployment rose, the housing market collapsed, and many major corporations were left in ruins. This recession persists, leading us to question: how did this happen, and how can we prevent it? The financial crisis was largely caused by shortsighted political decisions that pressured banks and companies into issuing sub-prime loans within an already unstable financial system. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were also pressured to underwrite and convert these loans into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted, banks were short on capital reserves and passed the turmoil onto the repackaged mortgages they sold, impacting the wider economy.

The origins of the financial crisis can be traced back to the Clinton administration in 1999, as the President sought to boost his popularity for re-election. The administration eased lending restrictions, setting the stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. As reported by Steven Holmes of the New York Times in 1999, "Fannie Mae, the country's largest mortgage underwriter, faced increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and middle-income people and from shareholders to sustain its profit growth." Holmes foresaw the potential consequences: "But the government-backed corporation might encounter trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a bailout similar to the savings and loan crisis of the 1980s." As outlined in the introduction and predicted by Holmes, reckless lending practices would lead to economic collapse.

Several factors combined to send the economy into a tailspin, one being the complex new mortgage structures. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were extensively used before the crisis, further entangling the economy with the housing market. This led U.S. households and financial markets to overleverage, making them extremely vulnerable to even slight price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and financial institutions holding these mortgage-backed securities suffered. In 2007, the top five U.S. investment banks reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts, about 30% of the USA's GDP. Ultimately, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold cheaply, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley had to become commercial banks under strict regulation. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac held $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That moment in your story where you spread your authorial wings and soar, astonishing everyone with your captivating, even magical prose. Or the part where your readers fall asleep or click the "Back" button while cursing your name. Dr. Merlin is known to shout at her screen when she finds herself inundated with Too Much Information, and not even in an entertaining way.

Exposition is not your ally.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing advice, "Show, don't tell," yet Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages where nothing occurs, or worse, too much does. Exposition is the little devil on your shoulder, urging you to clear history to reach the good parts (not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder pushing the author to reveal every detail of each character's childhood).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, usually in straightforward prose. In films, exposition occurs when one character gives another a dump of information like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it is the author doing the telling.

An example is needed. As you read a story, you are informed that the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, they married in grand style, and her husband was murdered before her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to span two pages, during which both only exchange two lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to spend time on the husband's character, showing through his words and actions how deeply he loves his wife, and similarly, you would expect the heroine to demonstrate in various ways how his presence transformed and enriched her life (especially if the story flatly states this later). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally invested in his fate and provide insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, the depth of their bond, clues about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams as reflected through his eyes, and so on. You would grieve his death with her and thus grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect substance on the simple framework of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that substance. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, and presses on*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush through certain details. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, he's now a night manager at a gas station, has been married twice with no kids, likes to go fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first was NBC 4's live broadcast this morning (August 13, 2011). The top story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio, named Shad Hostettler, who had stabbed his wife, though her name wasn't given. They showed his mugshot, depicting him as quite menacing, and spent about two minutes on the unfolding story, mentioning that he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they allocated an appropriate amount of time to this story.

The second story was about an early morning shooting involving 18-year-old Travis Buyers. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and was critically injured; there were no arrests or suspects at the time. The SWAT Team was investigating. This story felt brief, which I suspect was because it involved a black man or took place in a black neighborhood. I've noticed over the years that when minorities are crime victims, they often receive less attention. If a white child or adult is kidnapped or missing, it gets extensive coverage; however, if it's a minority, it might barely be mentioned.

The next story was about a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. They provided details on where the incident likely occurred and identified the bullet as a .22 caliber from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers are offering a $5,000 reward for tips leading to the shooter's arrest.

The following story was about the rain and thunderstorms forecasted for Saturday afternoon. They mentioned that the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties over the weekend. The segment was brief, probably intended as a teaser to keep viewers engaged.

They also reported on a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus, describing the suspect as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie. He was said to be about six feet tall and weighing around 150 pounds. It seemed they spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing his race and skin tone.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted drug kingpin from Texas. He was found guilty of conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. I noticed they stated his sentence as "300 months" instead of 25 years, perhaps to make it sound harsher. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, which didn't seem particularly relevant to the story.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a type of security designed to track an index, commodity, or a basket of assets like an index fund, but it is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF offers the diversification of an index fund and the advantages of owning a single stock, such as the ability to short sell, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share in any transaction. While these benefits are highly attractive, the expense ratios of ETFs are much lower than those of average mutual funds. Unfortunately, there are some drawbacks, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just like a stock order. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available. Although these benefits are clearly stated, it is always a good practice for astute financial investors to assess whether the stated benefits, like diversification, truly exist and to what extent they do. For this purpose, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it with the top 10 holdings that constitute the ETF to determine whether the benefits of owning a single ETF are close to those of owning a diversified portfolio of ten stocks, and whether there are better configurations of the same stocks that could provide a more optimal Sharpe ratio or return.

To evaluate the ETF, including every holding would be cumbersome, so we have decided to include only the top ten holdings, which account for 63.58% of all assets in the ETF. Below are the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio was made up entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportions established by the ETF. The calculations of Beta and return are included in the chart below.

From the chart above, it is evident that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns. It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole. From the results completed thus far, it appears that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta. However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To evaluate whether these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation with that of the ETF IHF.

Looking back at Figure 17, there was a sharp decline in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was somewhat discouraging, and it's hard to pinpoint why it happened. With the arrival of winter at a New England campus, there is clearly a drop in people commuting by bicycle or on foot, which may account for some of the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester, when everyone is busy finishing schoolwork and processing grades. Filling out the commuter log might have slipped many people's minds. Additionally, December marks the busy holiday season and the subsequent month-long break for students and faculty, during which many do not need to come to campus at all. Classes then resume in late January for the spring semester, which might also be a reason for the low log numbers that month. However, none of this explains the low number of submissions in February. One might speculate that any project of this kind will have an initial burst of energy and excitement, which might naturally decline. To counter this trend, we launched Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign to reinvigorate the initiative, which did increase log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we faced was how to maintain project momentum amidst both a natural decrease in engagement and specifically the holiday and semester breaks experienced in higher education.

Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply ingrained in our culture. Therefore, it is crucial to provide incentives for engaging in alternative commuting modes. We distributed many prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. However, it would have been interesting to see how some even larger prizes might have impacted participation—such as giving away a nice bicycle, a hybrid car, or an electric car. This could have also helped to address the dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn't really change during the course of the project. However, if the prizes were to increase in value over the course of the project, that might have helped. Gift cards seemed more than adequate at the start of the project, but if we had announced in December the addition of a couple of bicycles, and then in January the addition of a hybrid or electric car, one can only think that participation and engagement would have increased instead of decreasing.

While exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I chose to watch all the trick films, numbering fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films typically use creative editing for illusions. My study focused on describing the poetics of most trick films and examining the evolutionary outliers in some of the later ones. Generally, trick films at the turn of the century are bound to a set, filmed within a front proscenium, with no camera movement, using long and medium shots, and adhering to a strict one shot = one film methodology. However, some early 20th-century films break these guidelines by introducing multiple shots.
One noticeable aspect shared by trick films is their filming on an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera remains fixed and does not follow the figures or objects. This composition was common in early films, rooted in theater, and for trick films, in vaudeville and magic acts. A limitation of using the stage is that figures in trick films generally move side-to-side and not towards or away from the camera. Take, for instance, the action in the film "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900). Actors enter from the right and move along the horizontal axis. Even when they exit the frame, the camera does not follow.
The frontal proscenium style also means that shots tend to be long shots, and less often, medium shots. Close-ups are never used in any trick films from the Edison catalog. This draws from the theater and vaudeville tradition, where audiences saw the entire performance at once, framed by the stage borders. As in most early films, actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.
Most early trick films follow the pattern of one conceptual shot equaling a film. This limits their length to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits their dramatic or narrative use; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks like magic, disappearing, and switching acts, with little story. However, in a trick film, a conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single “shot” may actually be several combined to create the illusion of appearing or disappearing. Look closely at "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A detailed inspection reveals the moment the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though the entire film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, in essence, an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt explains in "The Rise of the Gothic Novel." The Gothic style has faced criticism, praise, accusations of lacking depth, and admiration for its 'terrible sublime' aspect (Burke). Horace Walpole's "The Castle of Otranto," the original "Gothic Novel," combined elements of both "ancient and modern" romances to craft the proto-Gothic genre and a new literary expression. Walpole incorporates "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to present what he calls "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre includes many aspects of medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even at the time of its publication, "gothic" described various people, styles, and eras and was seen as archaic or unsophisticated when compared to "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The combination of theatrical "Gothic" with the new novel format (providing readers a more personal view of character psychology) has allowed Gothic literature to persist, appearing both outdated and new to readers distanced in time from its original writing.

A key Gothic idea found in Gothic novels is Chivalry. The medieval concept of chivalry, the training of a proper knight, is both preserved and adapted in the original Gothic novel, "The Castle of Otranto." Chivalry is especially significant to Gothic writers because it embodies the classic knight—brave, honorable, competent—and the perceived absence of this ideal in society, as noted by writers like Walpole. Through chivalric concepts, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized (foreshadowing the evolution from Gothic to Romantic) and is used to attempt to enhance the present. Walpole, writing "The Castle of Otranto" during political unrest, was despairing about the future. Immersed in politics and (possibly) unjust accusations, he might have thought, even if not directly, that the supposed morality and inherent "goodness" of the gothic era were lost in the individuals of contemporary society. This idea is clearly visible in several characters, such as Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, the reader is informed that he possesses many chivalric attributes; he is a prince who has suffered, been deeply affected by tragedy, and is believed to have been killed by infidels. The "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management involves the series of processes that move goods from a customer's order through the raw materials stage, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term "supply chain management" was coined by consultant Keith Oliver in 1982. Keith Oliver described the comprehensive process of planning, implementing, and controlling what happens in the supply chain to efficiently and promptly meet customer needs. There are six key elements in a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these six elements to provide the best customer service.

Production is the first step in the supply chain process and serves as the foundation for the entire system. The production stage outlines when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to understand customer desires, for which they can look to the market as the primary indicator of customer demand. Once managers have analyzed the market and understood customer demand, they are ready to decide what products to produce and in what quantities. After determining what and how much to produce, managers decide the best location and facility for manufacturing, considering customer demand and satisfaction. Once the production location is selected, the next focus is on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Production is a crucial step in the supply chain process, with every detail being vital. A lack of proper planning can result in significant time and financial losses for the company in the long run. For instance, I used to work at Walmart and Target retail stores, where both companies have a design, manual, and process for every business aspect, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments from trucks. Clearly outlined processes allow a company to operate smoothly without confusion over directions and expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply involves strategic decisions to determine a facility's core capabilities, and outsourcing partnerships should develop from these decisions. A company may have various production divisions for a single product, each with distinct equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must decide which division best fits the different processes of the product. Management might also choose to outsource work to other companies, primarily to create speed. Speed is the ability to deliver quality and flexibility while reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Victorian novels are known for their detailed attention and focus on the aristocracy of the era. However, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights" diverge from this tradition. Both novels incorporate elements of mystery and the bizarre, which were uncommon in novels of the time, strengthening the characters and providing insights into their motives and emotions.

"Now, many bewildering ideas crowded his mind. He seemed to be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily arguing: their words echoed in his ears; and when he noticed himself, he found he was talking to them... Suddenly, he was startled by the sound of gunfire; loud cries rose into the air; lights flashed before his eyes, and in the noise and chaos, an unseen hand hurriedly carried him away. Through all these rapid visions ran an undefined, uneasy awareness of pain, which tormented him incessantly." (Dickens, 220)

The two novels often utilize this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, although the content and function vary in each specific case. In "Oliver Twist," these strange events often reveal insights into Oliver's inner layers, his pains, and his awareness of the true nature of things happening around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, he relives it vividly, as if in a dream, while struggling to find help. The passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the unfolding events and the dire state of his health, vividly illustrated through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelms him; all his senses are numbed as he fails to notice the "unseen hand" that carries him away; he experiences despair anew, detached from the shock of pain, as the pain has become constant and linked with fear rather than surprise. As Oliver is overwhelmed, the question arises about whose will caused his misfortune, as it was certainly not his own. This shooting reinforces the idea that Oliver has little control over anything, as he cannot even attempt to influence the outcome of events, even when his life is at risk. This selection implies a growing sense of defeat in Oliver, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him into acceptance of this despair, affecting his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have at least made some effort for the sake of his own life.

"The day passed – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

A few years back, I was a tutor for elementary school students in an after-school program. My focus was helping them with subjects they found difficult, especially English and reading. One day, a teacher asked me to assist Adrian, a third or fourth grader struggling with reading. I realized something unusual was happening—he pronounced some letters perfectly, others not at all. It was peculiar, especially since he was of Latino descent but spoke perfect English. We faced challenges until I met his mother while supervising students during a field trip. She only spoke Spanish, and with my limited Spanish, we communicated. I then understood the problem: Adrian could read fine but was unfamiliar with the English alphabet. I'm unsure if this discovery helped him, but I hope he is improving now.

I tell this story to address language barriers in schools, especially in California. It shows that even children fluent in English can struggle with reading. Many recognize this issue, so what can be done? For Adrian, tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation, was key. For children who barely speak English, the solution is more complex. There's no single fix. A combination of dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, and ESL classes is necessary.

The dual language system is beneficial for all children, not just those whose first language is Spanish. Studies show children in bilingual programs often excel academically. There's concern these programs might waste resources and not benefit most children, but that's false. Making such programs standard rather than exceptional would benefit all. Should all teachers be bilingual? No, that's impractical. However, having bilingual aides or tutors is feasible.

From the time we are young, most of us are told that there exists something greater than ourselves, something beyond our understanding. Some attend Sunday school to learn about it, while others visit temples or look within for answers. Many of us easily accept the religions passed down by our parents. However, some completely reject them, denying the existence of anything beyond our self-centered universe. We might adopt one belief system only to later change our minds and switch to another. No matter which path we choose, we seek to define a part of ourselves through our unique spiritual perspectives. We search for a light in the darkness to guide us out of the shadows and into the sunlight.

"A cardinal," my father replied when I asked him his favorite type of bird. We sat on the porch, listening to the rain hammering the tin roof above us, smoking cigarettes together. The rain cascaded from the gutters, drowning the plants along the porch's edge. He looked out into the rain with a gaze that seemed half in search, half in memory. Over the past few months, he had grown thinner, his clothes hanging loosely on him. His hair was sparser than I remembered. He continued to gaze into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, scared, and unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him because discussing it would make it all too real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer to his, and joined him in watching the June twilight rain fall.

My father passed away that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation hadn't alleviated his suffering but extended his life a few months beyond the doctors' predictions; I couldn't define the value of prolonging his suffering. What kind of God would allow this, I questioned. Alone at night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, I felt he had long stopped listening to me.

I didn't want to witness him transition from this life to another. So, I didn't. I couldn't bear to watch the life that created me come to an end. I wanted to remember my father for how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, more than his family did, and knew he wouldn't want his only child to witness his death. I curled up in my bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of Republicanism. Though mainly an agriculturalist, his profession and brief political career made him known for his dedication and outspoken views on personal freedom and government. His commitment to an agrarian system formed the basis of almost all his governmental opinions. His attempts to preserve and promote what he viewed as the most superior profession influenced his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed that the United States had a significant opportunity to create an ideal system because there was no native tradition hindering the creators of the government, allowing for the establishment of a self-governing system. He strongly believed in the natural rights of man and that they are interdependent—meaning if one is denied, all fail, and the value of those remaining diminishes. Therefore, these rights should be beyond the reach of the government. He claimed that the so-called "state of nature" meant those with physical strength and malicious intelligence profited, but in civilization, this should not be the case.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must be established that accounts for the inherent good and evil within man. Taylor was very firm in his views on dualistic morality. He stated, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those protecting private property, improving agriculture, and discouraging capitalism, believing that a government founded on good principles would function equitably regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be driven by greed and self-interest. He saw self-interest as the motivation behind all human actions, but considered it evil only when it led beyond the creation of a society based on public good to sub-societies thriving at others' expense. A good government was necessary to restrain man's natural evil, and even then, it must be closely monitored to avoid adopting bad principles.

Taylor, like many other staunch Republicans of his time, called for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He wanted a very limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers than those explicitly stated in the Constitution. He understood that an extensive Federal government was costly and likely to become despotic. However, he also believed that a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous, as without reference to the writers' intent, such a method could easily become corrupt. Moreover, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more explicitly describes the country as a collection of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

I looked downward, my mind blankly absorbing the scene before me. Without emotion, silent, and with a practiced awareness, I analyzed the image before my eyes, refusing to relate it to any abstract understanding. Thoughts entered and left my mind almost as quickly as they appeared, so smoothly and cleanly that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and fluid experience of what I was observing.

Once, on the advice of an artist I worked with, I bought an art instruction book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." Since I was six, I had wanted to learn to draw, and this book covers everything from understanding what a pencil is to how the brain interprets lines. One technique it teaches is placing a square frame around any picture the artist wants to study, transforming an overwhelming detailed image, like a bowl of fruit on a kitchen table connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped picture.

At that moment, staring at the bowl before me, I couldn't mentally project the artist's frame. I was so overwhelmed and awed that I could only stand and gaze in wonder. Picasso had his blue period, Monet loved greenery, and Italian Renaissance masters showcased a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of seeing my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic, then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, "Work in Brown."

Fingertips lightly touched my chosen tool of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand moved through space, my mind's intent taking shape in what could have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Flakes of matter broke away and vanished. Muscles tightened, jerking and twitching a little more urgently the second time, as my hand hit the toilet handle again. The offending brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug at the bottom of the toilet.

Holding the mop loosely in hand, feet set a foot apart, a green tie uncomfortably knotted around my throat, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed matter someone had left for the unfortunate souls cleaning the Rite Aid bathrooms. A few more flushes, a few more tranquil, introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved toward the wall to my right, gripped the end of the toilet paper, and began wrapping itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand slowly dipped into the bowl, like a mother reaching into the oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are losing their lives while driving. Various factors come together to create a deadly statistical picture for young American drivers. The National Institutes of Health explains that one issue is that the teenage brain is not yet ready to handle the dangers of driving. A lack of experience is also at the heart of the problem. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also results in higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road.

Teenagers perform worse when traveling with peers, a fact that anyone with common sense knows happens frequently. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study showing a correlation between the age of passengers and the number of traffic accidents.

California and other states have tried to improve teen driver safety by requiring provisional licenses that limit the hours teens can drive and prohibit other minors as passengers.

However, in my opinion, provisional licenses are just temporary solutions. The real issue is that as a group, young drivers, by all statistical measures, are not adequately handling risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even at 18, individuals are too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research suggests a common desire among those under 19-20 to seek thrills. Hence, it makes sense to delay driving until this thrill-seeking tendency levels out. If we continue to issue licenses to young teens, not only will deadly accidents persist, but the death toll could reach alarming levels in the coming years. By 2010, the children of the Baby Boomers will be eligible to drive, with millions of new teen drivers ready to hit the road.

Legislation on this issue could be relatively straightforward. Schools could continue to offer driver education classes to start the learning process for future drivers, but no one under 18 should be allowed to operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued before granting a full driver's license, and a certain number of practical driving training hours would still be required. The specific number of hours could be based on what most states already require (in California, for example, it's currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Since the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from across all states, uniform national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable and effective way to protect teens nationwide.

The legislation I propose is by no means a novel idea.

This paper discusses three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Firstly, it provides a brief definition of the disorder. Then, it explains the diagnosis process, listing common characteristics or "red flags." Finally, it concludes with methods for teachers in mainstream classrooms to assist students with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), refers to the efficiency and effectiveness with which the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. More specifically, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information within the CNS and the neurobiological activities that underlie this processing, which generate electrophysiological auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This means it is a disorder where the central nervous system (i.e., the brain) cannot properly process heard information. People with CAPD have normal hearing and are not considered "hearing impaired"; rather, the part of the brain responsible for translating what we hear, distinguishing words or separating conversation from background noise, does not function as it typically should.

The earliest reference to what later became known as CAPD was in the mid-1950s, referred to as "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), when researchers were evaluating children with communication disorders. In 1954, the Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children; by 1961, Kimura "introduced dichotic listening tests and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the central auditory nervous system underlying dichotic perception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 encouraged research on children with CAPD.

CAPD manifests in various ways: individuals may be unable to localize or hear sounds spatially; may find it difficult to distinguish between two or more "acoustic events" (sound occurrences); may not recognize sound patterns; may be unable to detect changes in speech (such as detecting sarcasm based on tone changes); one sound may be masked by another; may lack the ability to synthesize auditory cues (i.e., interpret them meaningfully for action); and may struggle to determine the sequence of auditory information presented (Ferre).

To diagnose CAPD, a patient must be screened through "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on auditory function tests," which may be conducted by "audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, and others using various methods to assess auditory-related skills" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This might involve questionnaires, surveys, and observations of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. Currently, there is no single tool or test consistently used with high diagnostic success, and the cause of the disorder is unknown. Many tests present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and ask them to differentiate specific items, such as a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to these signals.

In pursuing an education in social work, I plan to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected and to support struggling families. The values I can contribute to the social work field include service, respect, ethics, a commitment to improving others' relationships, and enhancing my professional skills to remain competent. These core values are important not only to social workers but also to me personally.

I've always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path I wanted to take. Throughout high school and college, I saw many people avoid their problems and a few use less-than-ideal coping strategies. Because of these situations, I chose to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. Still uncertain about a career path, I decided to take a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy on her couch. She explained he was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police about his parents. To see if I could help, I went to his parents' house. Once there, I privately shared my concerns with the police and mentioned my recent Psychology degree from Piedmont College. The police asked me to speak with the parents since the law couldn't help the teenager. When I questioned the parents, they seemed nervous and made excuses, describing their son’s behavior as “manipulative” for involving outsiders in “simple” disputes. This experience prompted me to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with family disputes.

Another important value for social work is social justice. As a society, we claim to value the individual and mourn those we lose. However, society's concept of the “individual” often aligns more with outdated traditions than true uniqueness. If we mourn lost individuals, why do we strive to be like "everyone else?" I am an individual and dislike limiting myself to resemble others. Throughout high school and college, I protested against social injustice: dyeing my hair unconventional colors, wearing clothes that expressed my personality, piercing beyond traditional norms, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and fighting against racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it. I believe in social justice and will continue to protest against social injustice.

The paper discusses biological and sociocultural models related to insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information and medical aspects of health, while the sociocultural model examines environmental relationships and their application to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia considers these models and explains each piece of research selected to better elucidate them. The research findings are then critically evaluated to highlight their strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be categorized as primary sleep disorders, sleep disorders related to another mental disorder, or sleep disorders related to other issues. Primary sleep disorders include dyssomnias or parasomnias, while sleep disorders related to other mental disorders are associated with Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other categories may result from medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias include primary insomnia, primary hypersomnia, narcolepsy, breathing-related sleep disorder, circadian rhythm sleep disorder, and dyssomnia not otherwise specified. Primary insomnia involves inadequate or maintained sleep, whereas primary hypersomnia is characterized by difficulty staying awake, both lasting at least one month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM sleep. While dyssomnias focus on initiating and maintaining sleep, parasomnias involve behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias include nightmare disorder, sleep terror disorder, sleepwalking disorder, and parasomnias not otherwise specified. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (clinical disorders) or Axis II (personality disorders or mental retardation). The review focuses on insomnia and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in relation to biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspects of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin regulate sleep and wakefulness. This study with mice found phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons specifically responsible for sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep, and inhibiting its firing can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). These results suggest that the animal model of mice can be generalized to studies in humans, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for the human GABAB receptor. A problem or absence with this receptor could impair one's ability to achieve adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication is that if the phenotype is inherited, this could regulate sleep, and altering the receptor would naturally disturb an individual's sleep, negatively impacting aspects of life such as education, career, and daily tasks requiring focus.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around campus can be a challenge. During my freshman year, I lived in the East Halls dormitory, nearly the furthest eastern point of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in far-off locations like the Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes, especially when the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Talking to an alum not much older than me, I learned that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by large areas of unused land. Today, that empty space has been filled with sports fields, large new buildings including the new Creamery and health services building, and surrounded by apartments. As our campus continues to expand, moving from one place to another becomes increasingly difficult. What is the best solution to the mobility problem? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But bicycles alone won't solve any problems. Students need to use them, and the campus must be designed to accommodate cyclists' needs.

I was talking to a friend who recently resumed cycling after a break of several years. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. "Bikes are great," he said, "for a few years, it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Besides being good for your health, cycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off-campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I've made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have classes in the Thomas building, which is easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Cycling can reduce that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the most direct route to the Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, with or without a bike. Walking has its merits too, but personally, I'm too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That's over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and so on. It's more time than I can afford.

Aldous Huxley, in his novel "Brave New World," critiques the impending threat of technology and the capitalist structure that reinforces it through the creation of a dystopia. The people in this society value community over the individual and are conditioned from the start to seek immediate happiness above all. Citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to a single ideology dictated by the World Controller. Viewed through the lens of Marxist theism, the author's underlying suspicions about the development of these systems become evident. Frequent Marxist terminology, like homogenization and reification, supports the idea that Huxley's novel comments on the flaws of the emerging economy of his time.

Capitalism is satirized using the Marxist concept known as false consciousness. Essentially, ordinary citizens are prevented from understanding their true economic relationships with other classes, as they are primarily focused on their own gain. This is seen as a result of the ideological control over the proletariat and common workers, which is clearly evident in the conditioning of people in "Brave New World." Common classes, like Delta and Gamma, lack true will; through hypnopaedia, the drive to consume, spend, and indulge is greatly enhanced. As previously stated, this is manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, the idea that social class groups are wholly dominated by another distinct group, is clearly used here. The lower classes are completely unaware of this manipulation, essentially 'buying into an ideology that supports that structure' (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes are born with the ability to recognize it but do nothing; few Alphas or Betas, beyond characters like Bernard, do more than accept their place. In fact, the interactions between social classes, as will be discussed in more detail, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In "Brave New World," there are no relationships between disparate individuals. The novel seems to refuse to distinguish its characters—even among major characters, depth is lacking. Perhaps Huxley suggests that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprives humans of free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do extremes of any emotion; instead, interactions remain superficial, illustrated by the men's comments about women focusing primarily on their appearance (i.e., pneumatic quality) and the women's unashamed comments about their encounters. Furthermore, each social class's complacency with their hierarchical status indicates the socioeconomic impact of capitalism. Their complete obedience to their role in the community reflects Marxist thoughts on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority over all else as long as they continue to consume, obey, and stay aligned with their peers.

Almost four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main topics of heated discussion was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is more relevant today than ever before. Looking back on events since 9/11, I have personally observed the mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance for Islam in America. I don’t think in 2001 we could have ever had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, who has a clear Muslim background in his family.

The biography of the Prophet intrigues me because, according to what I know of Muhammad's history, it contradicts his character. From my past knowledge, I thought Muhammad forced conversions to Islam, conquering tribes and then compelling them to embrace the religion. However, according to the biography, Muhammad is portrayed as a martyr, misunderstood, and even humble towards others. Subsequently, people came to see the 'truth' in his teachings one by one and sought him out.

Furthermore, there are striking similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. The most obvious example is when he multiplied mutton and milk to feed forty men. This style of writing makes me believe the authors intended to present Muhammad as a humble prophet who lived in truth and miracles without needing to prove anything. This kind of fallacy is troubling because it diminishes the miracle and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it seems like an attempt to borrow from the life and identity of Jesus through Muhammad.

The biography also contains many stories that suggest part of its agenda is to provide evidence of ‘witness’ or how people ‘spontaneously’ converted to Islam. The issue, however, is that many of these stories come from at least a third-party perspective, with the author narrating that he heard from someone who heard from someone else. I didn't like this much, as I felt it weakened the stories and made them seem more suspicious, despite their intention to prove their truth.

What bothers me most about this work is the attempt to exalt Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. But history contradicts the notion that Muhammad was gentle and humble, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today know the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings and beliefs held by Jesus during his lifetime were quickly set aside as Christian thought evolved after his death. Observing this history broadly, we see Christianity drifting further from its origins. Today's world shows an increasing awareness and an unprecedented tendency towards progress. While traditionalists still exist and resist thinking beyond what they were taught, they may not be numerous enough to influence the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness will grow significantly in the coming years. There will be a widespread desire to distinguish the doctrines added to Christianity over time from the true intentions of its founder. Although it may take decades or even centuries, the outcome is inevitable: there will be a significant reversal in the trend of Christian history, moving back towards its original form. A movement will grow, stripping away layers of doctrine one by one, as if the clock is turning backward, until only the concepts Jesus introduced on behalf of God remain, before any other thinkers made such claims. As this trend sweeps across the United States and Europe, influencing people to worship as if living in Jesus' time, following solely his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, because the theological clock will have moved backward, the extreme diversity in Christendom will reverse into more uniformity in belief and practice. Across regions, denominations, and divisions of all kinds, we will see increasing similarities rather than differences. Human history is full of great reversions. For example, Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, but later that empire became a Christian institution. Our country has transitioned from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The coming great reversion will unfold within the Christian religion, undoing history in a search for its source, and reducing diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that part of what will enable this process is interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically rather than literally. So, what has happened since Jesus' lifetime? If we look far enough back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological starting point for Christianity. By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 BCE, monotheism, the notion of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion. The Jewish people did not share a unified spirit; they were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of common people.

I believe that "The Jungle" illustrates the innate greed and self-centered nature of humans. People primarily focus on benefiting themselves and improving their lives, often neglecting those less fortunate. The story highlights this through various examples, especially the factory owners and managers who are solely interested in expanding their companies and factories. They disregard anyone or anything obstructing their path or harmed by their progress. Upton Sinclair's work describes the scene vividly: "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there, from the mass, rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair aims to depict the severe damage caused by such pollution. He shows that the owners have no consideration for any person or animal that might be hurt. They ignore the massive smoke plumes from the factories and the runoff of animal waste surrounding Packingtown. The owners and managers are indifferent to the well-being of their employees who labor to make them wealthy. They will do anything to earn or save an extra dollar, "From top to bottom, the place is a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere, and no place where a man counts for anything against a dollar." They impose long working hours on employees and lay off large groups without notice, compensation, or assistance in finding new jobs. During the era depicted in "The Jungle," there were few, if any, laws protecting workers' safety or welfare, allowing managers and owners to act without restraint, pushing employees to work faster under poor conditions. Although the book doesn't explicitly state it, those who toiled in Packingtown were expected to endure the harsh conditions both at work and at home. There were no agencies or organizations to provide information or support to workers. Unions existed but often exploited the poor workers instead of helping them. The workers were treated so poorly and had no escape from the system, leading them to be described as slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, always on the verge of starvation and dependent on the whims of men as brutal and unscrupulous as old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is as inevitable and prevalent as in the system of chattel slavery."

Dream-land is considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's notable poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used this term to refer to an island north of Britain, which the Greeks thought was the edge of the known world. It is certain that Virgil used this term, but there is a more recent source worth noting. Poe was very interested in German authors. This quote is important because it shows Poe's familiarity with Goethe's work. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," comments on the similarity of their two poems, concluding that Poe was imitating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature states that Goethe was a celebrated writer of the poetic drama "Faust," which was published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's death. Within the verse of the second part of "Faust" is a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." The poem tells the story of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. After his wife passes, he begins drinking heavily and crying over the memory of his dead queen. He then decides it is his time to die, and he gives his possessions to his children, except for the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The demeanor of the King of Thule and the description of the king in "Dream-Land" are very similar, perhaps a dark reflection of Poe's loss and reliance on drinking. "Faust" was also adapted into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, less than a year before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. In "The Pit and the Pendulum," Poe mentions "ultma Thule," but he uses this phrase twice in "Dream-Land," as bookends for the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark, lonely, haunted by dead friends, and a shadowy world without color. All these scenes can be found in Goethe's "The King of Thule," as he has just lost his wife, feels lonely, and has lost his will to rule or even live. The entire poem is as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's poem.

Goethe was a significant author whom Poe would have known, if for no other reason than his respect for Tennyson. When asked if he admired Tennyson, Poe had this to say. Aside from the connection to Tennyson, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe's work through the many reproductions that took place after the original publication.

Under California law, a customer injured from slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store could potentially be awarded punitive damages if they show the store manager acted with malice. This could be argued if the manager was informed twice about the spill but ignored it for half an hour due to having dinner.

A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages hastily. To justify punitive damages, the plaintiff must present evidence that the defendant's actions were done with a willful and conscious disregard for probable harm and that the conduct was despicable. Palmer could argue that Martin should have known the potential harm of not cleaning the spill, as several D&D customers had been injured from slipping in previous months; despite this knowledge, he failed to clean it up. Although Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable is less convincing, it is still reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009 and Martin took no appropriate actions to ensure the store's safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, of an applesauce spill in the aisle. Martin told Wayne he was on a dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Martin of the spill, receiving the same response. At 5:30 pm on the same day, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill, seriously injuring her back. Before Palmer's accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of a non-contractual obligation if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." According to Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010), malice is defined as conduct intended to cause harm, or in the absence of intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and carried out with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when it is done with a conscious disregard for the plaintiff's rights, with the defendant "being aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct and willfully and deliberately failing to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She always felt like something was missing in her life; a desire that never seemed to be satisfied. It began when she was about 14, just entering her teenage years, and persisted until she was 17. By then, she realized she was looking for a person rather than a thing. However, she found herself uninterested in any boys. Some were attracted to her and tried awkwardly to win her over, but none appealed to her. She often questioned herself about this strange feeling, trying to figure out why something like this would happen to a teenage girl. Over the years, she developed some theories, but none were convincing enough to dwell on. So she lived her life, constantly questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were good and calm people who rarely argued, even with her. The only disputes were about her expressing her independence and free spirit. Although the daughter of a calm couple, she contrasted their energy with her lively and fun personality, which made her very likable, as she was a kind person.

Today, however, was not a calm day. As she moved from room to room, seeking new inspiration, she heard a short scream from the kitchen—her mother's beautiful voice. She rushed into the room, panicking, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She found her mother on the ground, appearing to be in pain, repeatedly saying "Ow" in short breaths. The daughter rushed to her side to help. "Ouch... darling, I... need you to take me... to the hospital." The words were hurried and tight, and her daughter could see she was in great pain. "Okay, Mom, just tell me how to get you there." Her mother directed her hands, and in that moment, the daughter was grateful for the strength training she had done. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back, and drove off.

The hospital visit came with the scents of disinfectant and illness, tinged with fear. But she wasn't aware of this, as her mind was focused on helping her mother. She quickly carried her injured mother inside, calling for help from the doctors. Several worried faces gathered, and someone quickly brought a rolling bed for her mother. They took her to be examined immediately, leaving the daughter to sit and worry.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while trying to reach a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study aimed to demonstrate that adherence to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean diet score" (aMed diet score), is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, with reduced intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies documented an inverse relationship between adherence to the Med diet and total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, with an intervention trial showing the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total cholesterol to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Prior studies did not focus specifically on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 without a history of CVD or diabetes, who were participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20-year period. FFQs were validated through studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. When records were unavailable, cases were considered "probable" and included, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts classified this way. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated for each FFQ, and leisure-time physical activity was assessed from 1986 onward.

To minimize random individual variation and better reflect long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from the prior two years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could potentially obscure results) by accounting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to evaluate the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of CHD and stroke incidents in women. During the 20-year follow-up, 2,391 cases of incident CHD, 1,763 cases of incident stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combining fatal CHD and strokes) were identified. Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk of CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign reads, "Hitler is alive in Burma."

Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner with a piece of cardboard held above her head, bearing a disturbing message written in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country ruled by an authoritarian military junta that came to power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, there were several street protests, marking the first public demonstrations in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests were called the "Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. After the initial uprisings, the public began to take an interest in the protests, and although the Burmese government initially allowed the monks to gather peacefully, the violence soon escalated into what some saw as an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and looting monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were arrested and imprisoned on sight, and a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007, simply for being present at a protest. While the official death toll was reported as 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army days before the official report, claimed, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you've heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the latest examples of atrocities in our world, the desire of governments to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over their citizens has been around since the dawn of civilization. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have absolute authority over all aspects of society. Japanese emperors are believed to be gods sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well-known examples of these actions include the June 4, 1989, protests at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the government's authoritarian rule. The death toll in that instance varies widely, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead, while the Chinese Red Cross reported 2,000-3,000 deaths. Another example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, systematically killed all Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of their ethnic background. Hitler's 'Third Reich' is another extreme example, a period spanning several years and countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed.

Duke Ellington's contribution to jazz is largely attributed to his long career and his creative ability to shape his orchestra.
